g.text: GDT — Six Entries After M4 (each 8 bytes)
Entries 1–4: S=1 → code or data segment.
G=0: **byte granularity** (limit counts bytes, not 4KB pages).

g.text: GDT[5] — TSS Descriptor Byte Layout (8 bytes)
Ring-3 Interrupt Arrival → Hardware Stack Switch Sequence
Critical Invariant: TSS.ESP0 Must Be Updated on Every Context Switch
+0x04 esp0 uint32_t ◀ KERNEL STACK PTR — ONLY FIELD THAT MATTERS
+0x08 ss0 uint32_t ◀ KERNEL STACK SEG = 0x10 — ONLY OTHER ACTIVE FIELD
+0x1C cr3_field uint32_t [0x00000000 — HW task switch only]
+0x64 trap uint16_t [0x0000 — no debug trap on task switch]
+0x66 iomap_base uint16_t [0x0068 = sizeof(tss_t) → no ring-3 I/O]
| Idx | Selector | Name | S | DPL | Type | Access | flags_limit |

g.text: Byte 5: access = 0x89 → P=1 DPL=00 S=0 Type=1001
Byte 6: flags_lim = 0x00 → G=0 D=0 L=0 AVL=0 | limit[19:16]=0
ltr 0x28 — loads TR (Task Register) with TSS selector

text.tspan: ① Timer IRQ fires (PIT IRQ0 → vector 32)
② CPU checks EFLAGS.IF = 1 → interrupt accepted
Detects CPL=3 → DPL=0: privilege change required
③ CPU reads TSS.ESP0 and TSS.SS0
(hardware reads physical bytes at kernel_tss+4 and +8)
⑤ CPU pushes 5 values onto KERNEL stack (high→low):
⑥ isr_32 stub executes → isr_common_stub → interrupt_dispatch
Pops EIP, CS → sees CS.RPL=3 > CPL=0 → privilege change back
Also pops EFLAGS, ESP, SS → restores ring-3 stack
User process resumes at exact interrupted instruction

g.text: If ESP0 is stale (points to old process's stack_top):
→ Next ring-3 interrupt pushes frame onto WRONG stack
→ Corrupts old process's kernel state silently
→ System crashes unpredictably later, not immediately
→ Hardest class of bug to diagnose in OS development
